<h3>GABA Modulation</h3>

<p>Selank's primary anxiolytic mechanism is indirect enhancement of GABAergic signaling. Unlike benzodiazepines, which bind directly to GABA-A receptors, Selank modulates the system without causing sedation, tolerance, or withdrawal (<a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/12918027/">Seredenin et al., 2002</a>).</p>

<p>This distinction matters enormously. Direct GABA receptor agonists suppress cognition and create physical dependence. Selank achieves anxiety reduction through a gentler mechanism that preserves (and even enhances) mental clarity.</p>

<h3>Serotonin Balancing</h3>

<p>Selank modulates serotonin metabolism in key brain regions, particularly the hypothalamus and frontal cortex (<a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/12675140/">Narkevich et al., 2008</a>). This contributes to mood stabilization and reduced rumination without the blunting effect that SSRIs can produce.</p>

<h3>Enkephalin Preservation</h3>

<p>Selank inhibits enzymes that break down enkephalins, the body's natural opioid-like stress buffers. By slowing their degradation, Selank increases enkephalin availability without directly stimulating opioid receptors. There's no sedation, no euphoria, and no dependency risk.</p>

<h3>Tuftsin-Derived Immune Support</h3>

<p>As a tuftsin analog, Selank retains the parent peptide's ability to stimulate phagocyte activity and natural killer cells. Russian clinical data shows NK cell activity increases of roughly 25% in stressed subjects. This immune modulation may partly explain the antidepressant-like effects, given the established links between chronic inflammation and depression.</p>

<div class="d-t">
  <div class="s">Key Finding</div>
  <p>Rodent studies show Selank increases BDNF production by up to 40% in hippocampal regions. BDNF supports neuroplasticity, the brain's ability to form new connections, making Selank relevant for both anxiety management and cognitive enhancement.</p>
</div>

